review_blob: 330 ml bottle from The Party Source at home. Pours a hazy orange amber color with a fine off white head. The aroma was sweet, candi sugar, floral, caramel and mild dark fruits. The flavor has caramelized sugar, figs, nutmeg and some other spices, oak, the port barrel adds a different layer of sweetness, light tannins and hints of alcohol. It opens tingly, but the finish is dry. Medium bodied. This is probably my favorite of the three versions Ive had so far.

330 ml bottle purchased locally. Pours a hazy golden orange brown color with a fine off white head. The aroma was sweet, candi sugar, floral, caramel and mild dark fruits. The flavor has caramelized sugar, figs, stonefruit, nutmeg and some other spices, bubblegum and hints of alcohol. It opens tingly, but the finish is dry. Medium bodied. Decent, but not one that I would revisit.

330 ml bottle shared by jmborggren. Pours a slightly hazy dark amber color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor come off more wild and woody than oud bruin, tart fruit, cherry, wine barrel funk, lightly acidic, a hint of spice, decent.

750 ml bottle shared with Tmoney99. Pours a hazy golden color with a large fluffy off white head (actually a bit of a gusher upon opening). The aroma and flavor have pale toasted malts, grass, moderate funk, nice fruity character, hints of peppery spice, dry, hay, doughy bread, oak, mild Chardonnay/vinous character, overall nice saison that I will revisit next time Im there.
beer_name: Little Fish Barrel-Aged Saison du Poisson

review_blob: Draft to taster at Madtree. Pours a hazy amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have quite a bit of herbal and floral hops, earthy, light citrus, pale malts, lightly toasted bread, the tea shows up in the finish, mild bitterness, decent session pale ale.

Draft to taster at Madtree. Pours a clear golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have pale malts, light wheat, a spicy rye bite, very light citrus, earthy hops, moderate bitterness, not much flavor to the finish.

Draft to taster at Madtree. Pours a slightly hazy golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have lemony citrus, herbal, light mint, floral, mild to moderate bitterness, actually the finish is more floral like chewing on the petals of a flower, again, an interesting enough beer.

Draft to taster at Madtree. Pours a hazy amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have an interesting smoked character, not meaty, not really woody, more like smoked grape skins, earthy, lightly funky, some fruity, mild to moderate bitterness to the finish, interesting beer.

Draft to taster at Madtree. Pours a clear light golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have pale malts, light mint, the ginger is also lighter and brings a mild cleaner like quality, additional herbal notes, light fruit, the finish is soft, just ok.

Bottle from The Party Source. Pours a slightly hazy amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have big floral, herbal hops, a minty character, some lactic acidity, tart, odd fruity notes, some bitterness to the finish as well as a lingering herbal character that is like one of the components was reduced to an oil, strange beer.

Draft to taster at Dutchs. Pours a slightly hazy golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have the cocoa and sweet vanilla over a light bready malt base, a splash of caramel and fruit, finishes with mild bitterness, soft overall.

16 oz can from Cappys at home. Pours dark brown in color with a medium sized beige head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malt, chocolate, mild maple syrup, caramel, some ash to the finish, a bit too thin and just very average in my opinion, the Imperial Ipa was solid.

16 oz can from Cappys at home. Pours a hazy golden color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor have big earthy, herbal hops, some green onion character, light citrus, dank character, pale toasted malts, some caramel, moderate bitterness to the finish, decent enough imperial Ipa.
beer_name: Nickel Brook Immodest Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: 750 ml bottle shared by eyedrinkale at Kuhnhenn in 08 and again from a growler picked up in Kentucky in 2010 from notes. Pours a hazy caramel brown color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have sweet malts, caramel, toffee, some toasted malt, stronger bourbon, a splash of vanilla and wood, a little funk, interesting.

Draft at Deweys while waiting on pizza from notes. Pours a slightly hazy amber color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor have toasted bread, biscuits, a splash of caramel, light nutty character, mild hop character, light herbal, light earthy hops, mild bitterness, ipa?, ok for what it is.
beer_name: Mt. Carmel DewBrew Red Apron IPA

review_blob: 500 ml bottle first tasted at a bottle share, this is from one I shared with the group from notes. Pours a clear golden color with a thin off white film. The aroma and flavor have tart/sour citrus, vinous character, wood, Brett, white wine, acidic, apple skins, cider like at times, light pithy character, a solid drinking beer, enjoyable.

12 oz bottle from Cappys at home. Pours dark brown to black in color with a medium sized creamy beige head. The aroma has roasted malts, coffee and a mix of dark and milk chocolate. The flavor has roasted malts, dark chocolate, mocha coffee, more milk chocolate at the finish, decent roasted bitterness grows with warming, very creamy smooth mouthfeel, light barrel character, nice.
beer_name: New Holland Dragons Milk Reserve - Coffee and Chocolate (Indulgence)

review_blob: Draft at Fifty West. Pours a clear golden color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor have citrus, grapefruit, and tropical fruit notes, grass, some resin character more on the flavor, pale toasted malts, mild sweetness, the finish has a strong bitterness, this fits the mold for an imperial ipa, stronger hop character, bigger malt bill, very good.
beer_name: Fifty West Done In A Day IPA

review_blob: 750 ml bottle shared by phaleslu from notes. Pours a hazy golden color with orange highlights and a small white head. The aroma and flavor had a nice overall fruit character, tart, funky, yogurt, mild Brett character, oak, citrus, blood orange, easy to drink now, I would like to revisit this sometime in the future to see what the additional time for the Brett to work does to the beer, solid now.

12 oz bottle from Dutchs at home. Pours a hazy yellow golden color with a medium sized white head. The aroma and flavor have citrus, light pine, some sweetness, tonic water, some floral notes, quite a bit of lime, really does come off like a gin and tonic, some mineral character to the finish, interesting beer.

Draft locally (also from a bottle). Pours a hazy golden color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor have the character from the base beer, sweet malts, mild toast, grass, coriander and additional mild spice, some of the lemon peel comes through especially on the nose, mild funk, with some barrel influences, wood, cab barrel, with mild Brett funk, curious to see how this develops with time, interesting.

19.2 oz. can shared by jmborggren. Pours a thick black color with a small, dense dark tan head. The aroma and flavor have big roasted malt, dark chocolate, caramel, mocha, earthy hops, a smooth sweetness from the oats. The barrel adds to the complexity of the beer and some booze, mainly warming, the bourbon is noticeable, vanilla, wood, this is really good now, but some have suggested waiting longer. This is one of those beers that I would enjoy whether on draft or out of the can, there is something very satisfying about pouring an Imperial stout from a can.
beer_name: Oskar Blues Ten FIDY - Barrel Aged

review_blob: Draft at Rock Bottom Cincinnati. Pours dark brown to black in color with a small beige head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malt and coffee, some nutty character, vanilla and chocolate but this was a pretty straightforward coffee stout, tasty, medium body at best, decent surprise.

12 oz can shared by Tmoney99 from notes. Pours a clear dark amber/copper color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have caramel, grapefruit citrus, resiny and earthy hops, spicy rye, toasted bread, moderate bitterness, decent enough ipa.

10.5 oz bottle from The Party Source. Pours dark brown to black in color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have tart fruits, caramel, oak, tobacco, berries, hints of vinous character, a blend of sweet and sour, aside from a slight burn at the finish, not much of an alcohol presence even at greater than 11%, overall decent but not something I would revisit.

Draft to half snifter at Dutchs. Pours a clear cola brown color with a small off white head. The aroma has sweet malts, tart fruit, actually shows some hints of sour character. The flavor is more bready, a splash of caramel and chocolate, the Brett character is very mild right now, stone fruit, cherry, figs, lightly tart, maybe this needs more time to develop, but I have had better from these guys.

Draft at Dutchs for the second day in a row. Pours a hazy orange golden color with a small off white head. The aroma has citrus, grapefruit, resin and dank, earthy hops. The flavor has more earthy and green onion character, grapefruit, citrus, resin, caramel, moderate bitterness, the second glass had a stronger onion character than the first time, it mostly works with this beer, but I am not a fan of onions, carries the abv nicely.

Draft to taster at Dutchs. Pours a clear dark golden/light amber color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma and flavor have pale toasted bready malts, caramel, grass, noble hops, moderate bitterness for the style, German malts, some spicy hops, interesting take on the style.

500 ml bottle shared with Tmoney99 thanks to Errl. Pours a slightly hazy deep reddish purple mahogany color with an initially large fluffy pinkish head that settled quickly. The aroma and flavor have big raspberry jam fruity character, tart, oak, tannins, some acidity, I am a big fan of this, this has the pop of a Blushing Monk with the abv of Rubaeus, if I could get this in cans I would drink a ton of this on the golf course.

500 ml bottle shared by Tmoney99. Pours a deep reddish amber brown color with a small off white head. The aroma had dark fruits, raisins, vinous character, vanilla, wood, some tart character, interesting. The flavor had much of the same with more vanilla, bourbon, chocolate, caramel, floral notes, much more interesting than the base beer, my only negative is the bigger sweetness, still solid.
beer_name: MadTree Bourbon Barrel Aged Dead Flowers With Brettanomyces

review_blob: Draft to taster at Cappys from notes. Pours a hazy orange golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have sweet malts, caramel, toasted grains, citrus and herbal hops, moderate bitterness, American barley wine if we stick with barley wine as its style, additional fruit character, warming alcohol, decent enough.

Draft at Listermann from notes. Pours a hazy orange amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have citrus, herbal hop character, grass, mild floral notes, toasted bready malts, fuller body, moderate bitterness, some spicy hops, orange zest, dry finish, solid DIPA

375 ml bottle from The Party Source. Pours a hazy dark golden/light amber color with a large, fluffy eggshell head. The aroma and flavor have mildly tart citrus, Brett funk, this leans more on the wild side than sour, dry, pale malts, bready, some white wine vinous character, barnyard, oak, some hoppy bitterness to the finish.

Draft at Firehouse grill. Pours a hazy orange golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have bigger citrus and tropical fruits, pale malts, lightly toasted, bread, resiny hops, some dank character, bitterness grew as I moved through the glass, very solid.

12 oz bottle from Brian shared with drsordr. Pours a hazy golden orange color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have big, juicy citrus fruits, tropical fruits, spicy hops, mild to moderate bitterness, very fresh, pale malts, lightly toasted, bitterness grew, very solid.

Draft to taster at Dutchs. Pours a clear amber color with a small off white head. The aroma has some fruit mentioned in the deScription, strawberry and citrus. The flavor has more more balanced character, strawberry, banana, caramel, toasted bread, mild Belgian character, yeast, mild bitterness, decent enough.

Draft to taster at Dutchs. Pours a clear pale golden color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have grassy and herbal hops, pale Pilsner malts, lightly toasted bread, some subtle sweetness, just not too much for me to get excited about, light, lager, good for what it is but...

Draft to 4 oz taster at BC Bottle Logic. Pours a dark cola brown color with a small beige head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malts, dark chocolate, molasses, dark fruits, background coffee notes, earthy bitterness to the finish, nice beer.
beer_name: Nowhere In Particular Letters To The Underworld

review_blob: Draft to taster at Ei8ht Ball. Pours a hazy reddish purple amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have big tart/sour berries, wine barrel character, vinous, acidic, wood, lasting tart/vinous character through the finish, this was a surprise and I would have it again if around.
beer_name: Anderson Valley Horse Tongue Thribble - Currant

review_blob: Draft to 4 oz taster at Dutchs from notes. Pours a clear golden amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have big citrus, blood orange character, herbal hops, pale malt, decent bitterness to the finish, decent enough but I wouldnt seek this out again.
beer_name: Against the Grain / Mikkeller Bloody Show

review_blob: Bottle from b3shine shared with the group. Pours dark brown to black in color with a small khaki colored head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malt, dark chocolate, cinnamon, vanilla, spicy rye notes, coconut, sweetness and roasted malts blend nicely, very smooth, enjoyable.

Draft to half snifter at Churchkey. Pours dark brown to black in color with reddish highlights and a small beige head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malt, dark chocolate, coffee with a pervasive peated whiskey character, wood, smoky peat, some mild booze, I liked this better than I expected because Im not a fan of peated beers typically.

Draft to half snifter at Churchkey. Pours a hazy reddish amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have lightly tart raspberry but this is more fruity than anything, light spice, pale malts, light earthy notes, some acidity, ok.

Bottle at Churchkey split with someone I just met. Pours dark brown to black in color with a small khaki colored head. The aroma and flavor have a ton of peated whiskey and smoke, roasted malt and dark chocolate try to get in on the action, oak, a dab of coffee, you get every bit of the 15 months this spent in the barrel, not my favorite thing but this was well done.

Draft to half snifter at Churchkey. Pours dark brown to black in color with a smaller beige head than the base beer. The aroma and flavor have dark fruits, cherry is all over this, some roasted malt and chocolate come through, a light tart note to the cherry, more oily, less robust, I like the base beer better.

Draft to half snifter at Churchkey. Pours dark brown to black in color with a small beige head. The aroma and flavor have roasted malts, dark chocolate, some subtle coffee character, the lactose doesnt really come through in the flavor, but serves to smooth the beer a bit and provide a hint of sweetness,solid robust porter.

Draft at Churchkey. Pours a clear deep amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have sweet malts, caramel, sherry, wood, slight tart, the sugary notes, dark fruit, raisins, hint of spices, cocoa, the finish is a bit less sweet, red wine character, interesting brew.

Sampled from a 12 oz bottle shared by DrSilverworm. Pours a slightly hazy deep amber/copper color with a small disappearing off white head. The aroma and flavor have sweet malts, caramel, brown sugar, bourbon forward, vanilla, some dark fruit, raisins, this does come off a bit boozy, just ok.
beer_name: Dark Horse Bourbon Barrel Scotty Karate Scotch Ale

review_blob: 750 ml bottle shared by b3shine. Pours a hazy yellow golden color with a small white head. The aroma and flavor have tart citrus, tart apple juice, pale malts, a hint of mild sweet smoked character, yeast, herbal notes, mild spices, grass, decent enough.

Draft to taster at Dutchs. Pours a hazy orange amber color with a small off white head. The aroma and flavor have mildly tart citrus and funky tropical fruit character, something off and funky with this that made it hard to enjoy. Some caramel and pale malt, finishes tart, with that same funky character.
beer_name: Prairie / TRVE Prairie & Friends TRVE Edition Sour Red Farmhouse Ale
